⬇️ Use this script in your next job interview to answer “What are your salary expectations?” 

Companies ask you this question because they want to underpay you. They are hoping that you give one number like, “I am hoping to make $70k” 
 
There is NO reason why a company should NOT tell you what the position pays and there is NO reason that they should make you tell them what you want to be paid BEFORE they tell you the range of the position. 
 
So don’t fall for it and play the same game by answering their question with a question or giving them a non-answer. 
 
📌Use this script, 
 
Interviewer “What are your salary expectations?” 
 
You “ What is the position paying?” 
 
Interviewer “We really need to know what you want before we pass you on to the next round” 
 
You “Well, what’s the range? I am sure you have a pay range for this position.”
 
STAND YOUR GROUND and DON’T PANIC
 
👉If they answer and give you a range, you can say “I am amenable to that range” or “That is the range I am looking for” 
 
👉If they refuse to give you a range or tell you what they will pay you can say, “I’m very interested in this opportunity and I’d like to have this salary conversation after I’ve learned more about the role and the company.”
 
If they threaten to not pass you on to the next round, great! You dodged a bullet. 

Trust me, you don’t want to work for a company that won’t in the least disclose their salary range. 
 
Good luck 🍀

🤨 You might be wondering “what the heck are soft and hard skills?”

Soft skills = personal qualities that are applicable to any job 
Hard skills = learned skills that are specific to one job or industry 

Soft skills are non-technical, more interpersonal skills, examples: 
* Organization 
* Time management 
* Resourcefulness 
* Teamwork 
* Problem solving 
* Patience 
* Leadership 
* Communication
* Critical thinking  
* Etc. 

Hard skills are technical skills that must be learned, examples: 
* POS systems 
* CSS/HTML 
* Copywriting 
* Bartending  
* Adobe Illustrator  
* Microsoft Excel 
* Video Editing
* UX/UI design  
* Asana 
* SEO 
* Etc.

There are some skills that fall into both categories like “project management” or “time management” as these can refer to a personal quality or a specific software setup. So don’t over think it, but definitely be sure to include a balance of hard + soft skills when answering this question. #careeradvice #careertiktok #job #jobinterview #jobinterviewtips #jobinterviewquestions #careercoach #personaldevelopment #professional #interviewtips #interviewtipsandtricks

⬇️There’s only one right answer to these five interview questions. 

When you’re asked in a job interview, 
“How are you?” 

❌Do not say, “Ugh, I am just getting over a cold. I’ve been better”

✅Instead, always say, “I am great, thank you. How are you?”

@Anna Papalia 👈Watch this for more details on how to answer small talk questions in a job interview 

“Why do you want to work here?”

❌Do not say, “I went on your company’s website, and I really like your mission and values, and your tuition reimbursement plan is very interesting.” 

✅Instead, always say, “I’ve outgrown my current position, and I am looking for a new challenge and I know that I can improve your product and department by doing x, y and z.”

@Anna Papalia 👈Watch this to learn more about how to answer this question by explaining what you can do for the company not what the company can do for you.

“Where do you see yourself in 5 years?”

❌Do not say, “Well I want to go to grad school and start my own business.” 

✅Instead say, “I see myself here at this organization.”

“Do you have any questions for us?”

❌Do not say, “No. I’m good. You answered all my questions.”

✅Instead say, “Why is this position open?” and “What are the next steps in the interview process?” 

“What are your salary expectations?”

❌Do not ever give them a number 

✅Instead say, “What is the position paying?” 

@Anna Papalia 👈Watch this to learn how to negotiate your salary in a job interview

😱Never accept a job offer without negotiating.  When you receive a job offer always say, “Thank you so much, is this negotiable?” 

👉Watch @Anna Papalia Things I Don’t Want to See on Your Resume👈

❌You cannot accept a job offer and then try to negotiate because you don’t have any leverage. 

✅You have to negotiate your job offer before you accept. 

❌Do not go into a negotiation not knowing what you want and what you can ask for. 

👩🏼‍💻When they say they can’t increase your salary, you can negotiate other things: 

🔹Sign on bonus
🔹More PTO
🔹Better title
🔹Work from home/flexible schedule
🔹Tuition reimbursement 

👉Watch @Anna Papalia How to Answer, What Are Your Salary Expectations?”👈

👉Watch @Anna Papalia Things I Don’t Want to See in a Job Interview 👈

✅When you ask for what you want, state it plainly. 

❌Do not overexplain, do not say that you need more money because you have 4 kids in college” They don’t care. Their job is to figure out what you want and see if they can make it happen. 

✅It’s business not personal. 

✅Silence is power in a negotiation. 

⚠️If you try to leverage an existing offer to get more money you better believe they will ask to see your offer letter,  so it better be a real job offer.

Here’s what real leaders say instead:
✅ “What’s one thing slowing you down this week?”
(Cuts through noise—focuses on real roadblocks.)
✅ “Where do you need my help—or my silence?”
(That’s how you build trust and respect.)
✅ “What outcome are you proud of this week—and why?”
(Teaches your team to talk impact, not effort.)
📌 Leadership isn’t about being liked.
It’s about being clear, useful, and present.
Start your meetings like they matter. Or don’t bother starting them at all.

Want to sound more persuasive at work—without sounding pushy? Use these phrases.
Influence isn’t about volume.
It’s about language.
Here’s what the smartest professionals say to shift minds and move rooms.
💬 Comment “TEMPLATE” and I’ll send you 12 influence scripts you can use in meetings and emails.
Follow for more 👉 @yasarahmad_
—
I’m Yas, VP of HR—and I teach you how to win at work.
Here are 5 phrases that instantly make you more influential (backed by psychology, NLP & executive comms):
✅ “Would you be open to…”
💬 “Would you be open to exploring an alternative?”
→ Invites collaboration. Lowers resistance. NLP 101.
✅ “Most people in your position…”
💬 “Most leaders I’ve worked with value clarity over consensus—would that apply here too?”
→ Subtle social proof. Positions your point as the norm.
✅ “What would it take for you to feel comfortable with…”
💬 “What would it take for you to feel comfortable signing off today?”
→ Moves them from defense to solution mode.
✅ “You’re right… and here’s another way to look at it.”
→ Calms egos. Keeps control. Classic agreement frame.
✅ “Because…” (yes, really)
💬 “I’m suggesting this format because it’s worked in past launches.”
→ People are 2x more likely to say yes when given a reason.
📌 Influence isn’t force.
It’s frictionless.
Speak clearly. Speak strategically. That’s how you win the room.
